<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1918-04-02T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1918-04-02T00:00:00-05:00" n="65" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d65">
                            <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 600.119/620</note>
                            <head>
                                <hi rend="italic">The Counselor for the Department of State</hi>
                                    (<persName corresp="frus1918Supp01v01#p_PFL1" type="from"><hi rend="italic">Polk</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the
                                    Commercial Adviser of the British Embassy</hi> (<persName corresp="frus1918Supp01v01#p_CSR1" type="to"><hi rend="italic">Crawford</hi></persName>)</head>
                            <opener>
                                <dateline rendition="#right">
                                    <placeName>
                                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1918-04-02">
                                        <hi rend="italic">April 2, 1918</hi>.</date>
                                </dateline>
                            </opener>
                            <p>
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">My Dear Sir <persName corresp="frus1918Supp01v01#p_CSR1">Richard</persName></hi>:
                                I beg to acknowledge the receipt of your note of March 18, 1918,
                                enclosing a copy of a letter which you addressed to Mr. <persName corresp="frus1918Supp01v01#p_MVC1">Vance McCormick</persName> in
                                regard to steps which are being taken by neutral countries to exact
                                artificial prices from belligerents for commodities which they are
                                in a favorable position to supply.</p>
                            <p>In this connection I beg to inform you that, at a recent meeting of
                                the War Trade Board, it was resolved, after a discussion of the
                                question of the control of prices of exports to the northern
                                neutrals, that until a detailed plan for putting such control into
                                effect should have been submitted, that Board was not disposed to
                                express any approval of the principle of the control of prices of
                                exports.</p>
                            <p>I am [etc.]</p>
                            <closer>
                                <signed>
                                    <persName corresp="frus1918Supp01v01#p_PFL1">
                                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Frank L. Polk</hi>
                                    </persName>
                                </signed>
                            </closer>
                        </div>
                        </body></text></TEI>